New 'ABacc' to be added to school league tables
Schools and colleges face being ranked by the number of students they prepare for places at elite universities under Government reforms. Schools will be ranked by the number of pupils who gain the 'ABacc' under new plans. Photo: PA	By Graeme Paton, Education Editor
4:23PM BST 17 Oct 2012
Comments
New-style league tables could be drawn up to mark out schools with the highest proportion of “Russell Group ready” teenagers, it was revealed. The move would be made to ensure sixth-forms encourage more 16- to 18-year-olds to take rigorous academic subjects that act as a gateway to the most prestigious degree courses. The disclosure came as it emerged that the Government was planning to introduce the “Advanced Baccalaureate” – a new college leaving certificate. Under plans, teenagers will be awarded the so-called ABacc for successfully completing a 5,000 word dissertation-style essay and undertaking voluntary work – in addition to their three specialist A-level subjects. They will also be required to take one AS-level qualification in a subject completely unrelated to their three core disciplines to promote more breadth in their education. Related Articles
A-level shake up: Pupils 'should take practical courses', say Labour
17 Oct 2012
Young boys 'struggling to write their name'
17 Oct 2012
Students to be issued with graduation 'report cards'
03 Oct 2012
Top A-levels for degree courses revealed
23 Oct 2012
Teens opt for traditional subjects
16 Aug 2012
Foreign languages 'need bail-out'
16 Aug 2012
The Government said the plans – currently at a draft stage – were intended to make sure teenagers were better prepared for the demands of university, particularly elite institutions belonging to the Russell Group. It is believed that the proposals are being driven by Elizabeth Truss, the Tory MP for South West Norfolk, who was promoted to post of Education Minister in the recent Government reshuffle. She penned a report on the subject as a backbencher earlier this year in which she insisted that it schools and colleges could be ranked in league tables by the number of students they push towards the ABacc. “Schools should be measured on how many ‘Russell Group ready’ students they produce,” she said. “This should be through a new ABacc comprising three academic A-levels with at least an AS mathematics and AS humanity/language. “This should be the approach to get students from low income backgrounds into good universities.”
The planned introduction of the ABacc comes on top of a major overhaul of A-levels. Under proposals, existing bite-sized modules will be scrapped in favour of traditional end-of-year exams. More open-ended questions will also be introduced to stretch pupils further. Michael Gove, the Education Secretary, is also reforming exams for 14- to 16-year-olds by scrapping GCSEs in favour of new-style English Baccalaureate Certificates in the core subjects. Universities UK, the vice-chancellors’ umbrella group, said it welcomed Government efforts “to improve skills in extended writing, critical thinking and research”. But a spokesman added: “In terms of subject choices, however, it is important to remember that there is not a magic formula to gain entry on to specific university courses.”
The new proposals were condemned by teachers’ leaders who claimed they failed to cater for pupils more interested in entering the workplace – rather than university. Chris Keates, general secretary of the NASUWT, said: “This is another example of Michael Gove’s ideological manipulation of the school curriculum. “These changes are being made on the basis of his own personal prejudices rather than developing a curriculum which is fit for children and young people in the 21st century.”
Stephen Twigg, the shadow education secretary, said: "We support the concept of an ABacc, however Labour would ensure it includes a broad range of subjects... for vocational courses. “Michael Gove seems to be ignoring important subjects like computing and engineering which are critical for the modern economy."
