Instant Expert: the perfect cut-throat shave
Alex Glover, master barber at Murdock London, demonstrates the perfect traditional shave and explains that preparation and products are as important as the shave itself. By Sumant Bhatia, Video by Erica Elkhershi & Chris Stone
7:00AM BST 09 Oct 2013
Follow Comments
People who know me know that I get a five o'clock shadow at about 3.30. Perhaps even earlier, if I'm honest. So the team at Telegraph Men decided that my tough tufts of hair would provide the perfect test for Alex Glover, master barber at Murdock London a fashionable yet reassuringly old-fashioned barbers in Covent Garden. He does not flinch. Preparation is all-important. First, a cleanser is applied to get rid of yesterday's grime, followed by a pre-shave to soften the hairs, and an exfoliator (recommended three times a week) to banish dead skin. Next, Alex wraps a hot towel (50% boiling water to 50% cold) around my face to open the pores. There is no sign of a can of foam, or a trendy gel: instead there is a traditional shaving soap, lathered up in a dish, with a moist badger brush to keep it company. Alex applies the mixture on my face, and he insists that the more senior of his clients, who use this method, have the best-kept skin. Related Articles
How to make a classic champagne cocktail
02 Oct 2013
Beat stress just by controlling your diet
26 Sep 2013
How to know she's into you
17 Sep 2013
How to grow the perfect beard
10 Feb 2014
Facial hair championships held in Germany
