19 Sep 2013
He then produces the blade, and cuts in the direction of my hair growth, with intricate steps under the chin involving shaving both up and down. The razor-stage finished, Alex smothers me in a towel soaked in warm water to get rid of any residual soap, and also to stop my skin from drying out. Next, cold water to close the pores, and then an after-shave balm is applied above the shaving line. A cologne, splashed on to leave the skin smelling fragrant, provides the finishing touch. So, was this shave an indulgence? Of course. Could I do all these steps every day? Definitely not. However the thought of having healthier and younger-looking skin means that I will endeavour to use a badger brush in the future. Now if only Alex could find a way of making sure that the shadow does not re-appear quite so quickly... This video is part of Telegraph Men's Instant Expert series. The Filter
