Dettori, who became a global sports star after his Magnificent Seven at Ascot in 1996, was not available for comment nor was his business manager, Peter Burrell. One of the troubles with no, or very vague, statements – which do not even confirm which day the hearing is on – is that it will lead to a week of speculation as to the nature of the drug, which caused Dettori to fail the test. The jockey, who has entertained crowds with his flying dismounts for over two decades, has not taken a ride in this year’s valuable Japan Cup, a race he has won three times, on November 25. Perhaps that is not such a surprise now given the strict stance on drugs taken by the Japanese racing authorities. Early in his career, in 1993, Dettori was given a police caution after being caught with a small amount of cocaine in his pocket in London. In his autobiography he admitted that after some early success he had become a ‘tearaway, a night-club wolf, a drugs dabbler who was perilously close to seeing his career go permanently off the rails’. Speaking to the Daily Mail more recently he described the incident as the ‘best thing that happened to me, but I didn’t know it at the time. It was terrible at the time because I wanted to walk round with a big bag over my head."
In a Newsnight programme on the BBC he also admitted taking diuretics, chocolate laxatives and even Lasix, to keep his weight down, before the Jockey Club outlawed them in 1998. As a rule of thumb, British testers used to take a urine and breath sample of each jockey at least once a year but, among jockeys at least, there is a feeling that this has been upped this year. A minimum of one racecourse a week is selected by the testers and at it every jockey is breath tested – the threshold for alcohol is half what it is for driving – and a dozen will provide a urine sample from a random draw. When Kieran Fallon was banned by the French authorities after testing positive for a metabolite of a banned substance at Chantilly in 2009 he was banned six months. He tested positive again at Deauville on August 19 2007, a second offence for which he received an 18-month ban. Gallagher was banned by the French authorities for six months in 2000 having tested positive for cocaine on three occasions and was handed a further 18-month suspension when failing another test at Newton Abbott in September 2002. Horse Racing
